Opens Windows Defender / Windows Security settings / App & Browser Control → Exploit Protection settings

Start ms-settings:windowsdefender


Shows global system protections (mitigations) set for the entire Windows

Get-ProcessMitigation -System


Shows what exploit protections are set for a specific process, here for Microsoft Edge

Get-ProcessMitigation -Name msedge.exe



This command ALREADY changes system settings

Globally enables: 

- DEP (Data Execution Prevention)  DEP blocks execution of code in data memory

- SEHOP (Structured Exception Handler Overwrite Protection) SEHOP makes it harder for exploits to hijack exception handling

- CFG (Control Flow Guard)  That is, additional protection against exploits and malware. CFG makes it harder to jump to malicious code / ROP exploits

Set-ProcessMitigation -System -Enable DEP,SEHOP,CFG




Does not block anything; it only records what would have been blocked if the rule were active

Add-MpPreference -AttackSurfaceReductionRules_Ids <Rule_GUID> -AttackSurfaceReductionRules_Actions AuditMode


Blocks behavior considered risky

Add-MpPreference -AttackSurfaceReductionRules_Ids <Rule_GUID> -AttackSurfaceReductionRules_Actions Enabled





Shows the current Microsoft Defender settings, including, among others: AttackSurfaceReductionRules_Ids AttackSurfaceReductionRules_Actions
That is, you can check which ASR rules are added and whether they are in mode: 
0 = Disabled 
1 = Enabled 
2 = AuditMode 
6 = Warn <Rule_GUID> is the ID of a specific rule, e.g., a rule blocking suspicious script or process launches from Office. 
The safest approach is to first set rules to AuditMode, check that nothing important would be blocked, and only then change to Enabled.





